Marketing is the process of finding, anticipating and satisfying customer needs profitably. Marketing is a process of mutual satisfaction of exchange between customer and organisation. It’s not just about selling stuff. “It's about creating real value, building strong relationships and making sure customers are happy for the long haul.” Marketing is simply a business talking to its customers, selling the right product/service at the right time and in the right way. It’s a continuous process of studying customer behaviour, developing the right product, pricing them at right price, promoting them effectively and making them available at right place. Experts have also defined marketing in different ways. According to the American Marketing Association, marketing is “the activities and processes for creating, communicating, delivering and exchanging offerings that have value for customers, clients, partners and society at large.” Philip Kotler defined marketing as “the process of identifying and satisfying customer needs profitably.” This is the art of knowing the customer so well the product almost sells itself, as Peter Drucker said. Marketing is a mix of strategic and creative processes that add value, meet customer needs and achieve organizational goals.
Marketing and Outreach


It can be used to produce goods and services. Goods are tangible, services are not tangible. Marketing meets varying consumer needs. Nike has creative ad campaigns that market its athletic wear and shoes that emphasize quality, performance and style. Nike’s “Just Do It” campaign offers messages of power and resilience to athletes and fitness fanatics. But non-tangible services like Spotify have to sell benefits like personalized playlists, on demand streaming and ad free experiences. 
Industrial Marketing This is marketing to other businesses (not to individual people). “More often it’s bespoke solutions, long-term relationships. “IBM sells enterprise solutions to companies in areas like cloud computing, artificial intelligence and data analytics. They sell the solutions, showing how they can drive innovation and efficiency. IBM’s work with Wimbledon on AI-powered analytics and personalized fan experiences is a textbook example of industrial marketing in action and how a company can solve specific business challenges. 
Consumer Marketing Consumer marketing is marketing products to consumers for their own use. Coca-Cola and other brands localize their marketing to suit local cultures and traditions. For instance, Coca Cola uses unique packaging and seasonal ads in India to tap into the consumers’ emotions during Diwali and in the UK, during Christmas.  Brand loyalty is built through programs that connect the product to the customer’s major life events.
The fast growth of digital marketing technology and digital marketing as a powerful tool to reach the audience throughout the world. Companies use laser-like precision to target ads on sites like Google Ads, Facebook and Instagram. Look at ASOS, the online fashion retailer in the UK. ASOS uses digital marketing to showcase their collections of fashion to a worldwide audience. The focus on social media campaigns, influencer partnerships and targeted email marketing highlights the importance of digital channels in providing engaging and cost-effective outreach strategies.
Social Marketing Marketing combined with social responsibility. It looks after the society interests and fulfills the customer needs. Example: The Body Shop – focus on sustainability, cruelty free products and ethical sourcing. Campaigns like Forever Against Animal Testing and others are raising awareness of ethical practices that help build up trust and loyalty with customers, and help social improvement too. 
