3. Segmentation Benefits of segmentation **Enumerate the**
Market segmentation is the process of dividing a broad target market (consisting of consumers or businesses) into sub-groups of consumers (known as segments) on some shared characteristics. No two customers are the same. Everyone is different and has different needs. Companies segment their customers so that there is a common response to marketing strategies such as price , promotion and communication . Segmentation helps in developing tailor made marketing mix for each group rather than one size fits all approach. 
It is very important for a business to segment its market. It helps a business better understand its clients and improve the way it delivers services. companies can customize products for the needs of each segment, price them accordingly and develop targeted advertising campaigns. The companies can increase sales, develop a better relationship and increase customer satisfaction by targeting specific segments. Also helps companies to optimize resource allocation and enhance marketing decision making.  Nike is an example of segmentation where it targets different demographic groups such as athletes, fitness fanatics and casual consumers.  Nike is known for high performance sportswear for elite athletes, but Nike also has a comfortable and stylish selection for casual users. “The targeted approach lets Nike better position itself in each segment and be more successful in the marketplace.”

Benefits of Segmentation:
There are many benefits to market segmentation over undifferentiated marketing where the same strategy is used for all consumers. But markets are really differentiated groups of people with different needs, preferences and behaviour and it is not particularly useful to treat them all as one entity. A big, varied market broken into smaller, more homogenous groups. This process is known as segmentation . In this way, a business can gain a deeper understanding of their customers .  This way companies can adapt some products, pricing and promotion strategies for each segment rather than waste resources on one strategy that will not appeal to all.
1. Improved Customer Insight: Helps organizations to acquire a profound understanding of the needs, preferences and behaviors of different customer segments.
2. Targeted Marketing Strategies: It allows businesses to develop targeted marketing strategies for each segment rather than a one-size-fits-all approach.
3. Effective Deployment of Resources  It targets the most profitable or suitable segments and saves time, money and effort.
4. Improved Customer Satisfaction: Meeting the specific needs of each segment can lead to increased customer satisfaction and loyalty.
5. Sales and profitability growth. Targeted marketing is more effective; this helps to increase sales and profitability.
6. Competitive Edge helps companies to strategically understand the competition in each segment and to build a stronger market position.
7. Enhanced Product Development: Helps organizations develop products that meet the specific needs of various customer segments.
8. Setting Marketing Goals: It is useful in determining objectives and in evaluating the performance of each segment. 
Segmentation enables a business to target the most profitable or high potential segments of customers. So time, money and effort can be used more effectively. Help marketers to understand competitive space of each segment and make better strategies. Instead of trying to sell one product to all consumers, firms can produce different products to satisfy the needs of each group. This will mean more sales and more happy customers. When the market is segmented, marketing is more efficient, more targeted and more effective than when there is undifferentiated marketing. 




4. State the methods of pricing. One for each one of them:
Pricing strategies are an important part of marketing and assist companies in setting the right price for their products and services. Good pricing strategy is the one that covers cost and makes money and also attracts customers , builds brand image and is useful in competitive pricing . Business objectives, consumer demand and current market scenario lead to adoption of different pricing strategies. 
1. Mark-up pricing (full cost pricing)
The business adds a profit margin onto the total cost of producing the product. The total cost includes materials, labor and overhead costs. Let’s say the cost of making a shirt is 500 ₹. The company now adds a 20% mark-up for profit. Then selling price Rs 600 .
a) Pricing by Mark-up This method is simple and involves adding a fixed amount (or percentage) to the cost price. Widely used tool in the retail environment. For instance, a shopkeeper buys a product for ₹ 200 and sells it for ₹ 250. The mark up is Rs 50.
(b) Target Return Price (Break Even Price)  
This pricing method is based on a calculation of the point of equality between total revenue and total costs. When a business reaches its break-even point it begins to make a profit. For example, let us suppose that the total cost of the firm is Rs. 1,00,000. The price of each item is Rs. 100. The company needs to sell 1000 units to cover costs
c) Pricing at marginal cost
This method takes into account only variable costs, ignoring fixed costs. The aim is to cover variable costs and contribute to fixed costs. The marginal cost of carrying a few extra passengers is low , so airlines often discount last minute tickets .
2. Pricing based on value and competition 
d) Pricing based on value
The price customers put on a product is a function of the perceived value of the product. People think the product is premium and of better quality so the price of apples is high.
e) Value-Based Pricing
Price is also a function of customer perception, and the company will run promotions to increase that perceived value. Nike presents itself as a slim and high performing brand and as such charges a premium for its customers.
f) Pricing based on the Competition
Prices are fixed according to the strategies of competitors. They could sell their goods/services at a higher, lower or similar to the competition. If you buy toothpaste in a supermarket, it is the same price as your competitors so you can compete.                 
g) Closed bid prices
This is used in contracts where companies are secret bidding, trying to make the lowest possible competitive bid, not to lose money. For instance, companies competing for government contracts.
3. Demand and market price
h) Price skimming  
"The price is high at first, then it drops over time. Apple sells iPhones at a premium price and also discounted prices.
i) Penetration pricing ii) Low pricing in the market introduction stage to get rapid market share. For example, Jio entered the telecom industry with much lower prices to lure customers.
j) Pricing of premiums 
The price is intentionally high to give an image of quality and exclusivity. Rolex watches don’t come cheap they want to maintain their reputation as a luxury brand.
k) Price dynamics. 
Prices may vary depending on demand, time or availability. For example, the price of an airline ticket is high when travel demand is high.
