6. Write a short Note on Ethics in Marketing. 
Marketing ethics is the process of presenting products and services accurately, honestly and responsibly in relation with the customer, society and law. It is not just about rules, it is about doing things in a transparent, honest and respectful way and doing things to build trust in all of your marketing efforts. Today, with the highly conscious and connected customers via digital platforms, ethics is very relevant. Unethical practices can also damage a company’s reputation . For example, making false claims like ‘100% natural’ when the product is not, or collecting customer data without permission. But companies like the Body Shop and Patagonia that sell sustainable and cruelty-free products do ethical marketing and create higher trust and loyalty with their customers. Ethical marketing is many things such as truthful advertising (companies not over-selling), fair pricing (no hidden fees), respect of consumers’ privacy (especially online) and social responsibility (businesses considering their environmental and social impact.
Business Is Helped by Ethics in Many Ways. It gives confidence to the customers. It enhances the brand image. It builds loyalty and helps in long term profit. Ethics is a huge competitive advantage, customers are more likely to buy from brands that share their values. Any decision taken in marketing management can have ethical implications, be it product quality, correct pricing, honest promotional messages or protection of customer data in digital marketing. Amazon and Flipkart are clear about their prices and Google asks for user’s permission before collecting their data. Standards of ethics can help a company to avoid trouble with the law and to be successful in the long run in the face of competition and pressures to increase profits. 
Even if a small business does not have a lot of resources they can still be ethical marketers. They can be honest, transparent and accountable in everything they do. They should begin with information about their products or services. They shouldn't exaggerate in ways that could mislead customers. Honest advertising, keeping promises and transparent pricing with no hidden fees are simple things that go along way in building trust with customers.

Small businesses can also promote customer privacy by handling personal data responsibly and using it only with consent. They can also develop a good image by having moral relations with their employees and suppliers through decent wages and decent trade . For example, a small local bakery that is open about what goes into their products, uses quality products and treats their customers well can build long term loyalty without expensive marketing campaigns. 
Also ethics in marketing is very important for long run sustainability of business . Ethics creates trust. Your customers believe in you and will come back. Trust is the foundation of ethical companies that give knowledge consumers knowledge they can trust. Such trust is a good basis for further business development even in a competitive environment. Ethical marketing helps to avoid the risk of bad publicity, legal problems and damage to reputation which are very hard to recover from. This also means companies can stay ahead of changing customer expectations, as today’s consumers want to see responsible and trustworthy brands. For example, small green companies selling eco-friendly products are still doing great because their ethics are loved by consumers. Finally, ethics are important for the survival of small businesses as they create a good image and strong relations and thus sustainable growth in the market place leading to long term success. 
